    1	# Proposal 20: Étale Cohomology Point-Counting Shortcut — Results
    2	
    3	## Idea
    4	Use algebraic geometry point-counting (Grothendieck-Lefschetz trace formula)
    5	to compute pi(x) by encoding prime counting as counting F_p-points on varieties.
    6	
    7	## Results
    8	
    9	### Character sum approach
    10	- Correctly computes pi(x, q, a) = #{p <= x : p ≡ a mod q} for all tested
    11	  cases (q = 3, 5, 7, 11; x = 100, 1000)
    12	- BUT: the computation iterates over primes up to x, same cost as direct counting
    13	- Character sums just REORGANIZE the computation via Fourier analysis on (Z/qZ)*
    14	
    15	### Hasse-Weil constraint analysis
    16	| n | p(n) | Bits from 119 constraints | Bits needed |
    17	|---|------|--------------------------|-------------|
    18	| 100 | 541 | 480.4 | 9.1 |
    19	| 1000 | 7919 | 759.0 | 13.0 |
    20	| 5000 | 48611 | 807.3 | 15.6 |
    21	
    22	The constraints provide MORE than enough bits of information.
    23	**Catch**: computing each constraint requires pi(x, q, a), which is O(x^{2/3}).
    24	
    25	### Elliptic curve traces (y^2 = x^3 - x)
    26	- 167 a_p values computed, range [-62, 62], mean 0.168 (near 0 as expected)
    27	- Cumulative sum follows sqrt(pi(x)) (Sato-Tate)
    28	- Correlation with pi(x) residual: 0.39 — weak, not useful for prediction
    29	- EC point counts encode CURVE information, not prime distribution information
